<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><!DOCTYPE article  PUBLIC '-//OASIS//DTD DocBook XML V4.4//EN'  'http://www.docbook.org/xml/4.4/docbookx.dtd'><article><articleinfo><title>DevelopmentIdeas/LinuxOptimizedIO</title><revhistory><revision><revnumber>2</revnumber><date>2008-05-18 19:39:00</date><authorinitials>localhost</authorinitials><revremark>converted to 1.6 markup</revremark></revision><revision><revnumber>1</revnumber><date>2007-03-02 19:36:51</date><authorinitials>kinkie</authorinitials></revision></revhistory></articleinfo><section><title>Linux-Specific I/O Optimizations</title><para>Linux 2.6.17 (but the concepts were refined and interfaces altered in 2.6.18+) implemented a few new system calls for zero-copy I/O operations involving pipes: splice, tee and vmsplice </para><itemizedlist><listitem><para><emphasis>splice</emphasis> copies an user-specified amount data from a pipe into another pipe </para></listitem><listitem><para><emphasis>tee</emphasis> is like splice but doesn't consume data from the input, and can be thus invoked multiple times on the same pipe </para></listitem><listitem><para><emphasis>vmsplice</emphasis> copies data from an user-specified memory region into a pipe </para></listitem></itemizedlist><para>Those <emphasis><emphasis role="strong">might</emphasis></emphasis> be useful in different cases: respectively disk cache hit, cacheable miss and (probably) error pages. We need to verify that the semantics are right, and what kind of compromises are required to implement them </para><para><emphasis role="strong">Resources</emphasis>: </para><itemizedlist><listitem><para><ulink url="http://lwn.net/Articles/178199/"/> </para></listitem><listitem><para><ulink url="http://lwn.net/Articles/179492/"/> </para></listitem><listitem><para><ulink url="http://lwn.net/Articles/181169/"/> </para></listitem></itemizedlist><para><emphasis role="strong">Discussion </emphasis> </para></section></article>